                    <h5><strong>Why direct a one-act?</strong></h5>
                    <p>In the fall of 2014, I was given the opportunity to direct a one-act as my senior seminar project in the communications department at Trinity Christian College. While the idea of directing a show had never crossed my mind before, I jumped at the opportunity. One-acts at Trinity are a great way for seniors to demonstrate leadership in addition to many other skills needed for putting on a production. Other schools might treat one-acts as a lesser production, but Trinity emphasizes their importance as much as any other main stage production.</p>
                    <p><strong>About the Production</strong></p>
                    <p><i>The Real Inspector Hound</i> is a brilliant absurdist comedy. The show focuses around two theatre critics who are brought in to review a whodunnit murder mystery. As the show progresses, the critics are continually distracted by their own desires. One continually laments how he is the second string critic, while the other is swooned by the actresses wanting to take them out to a nice dinner, all while behind his wife's back. Eventually the two characters become apart of the performance they are reviewing, with an astonishing reveal of the real Inspector Hound.</p>
                    <p>The show had a cast of nine, with several technical aspects that required additional help from a stage manager, sound/light technician, and a stage crew member. The approximate run time was 70 minutes, with no intermission. The cast size and length was more extraneous than traditional one-acts at Trinity, but was able to be an exception and had the show approved.</p>
                    
